{title: Now Thank We All Our God}
{subtitle: Martin Rinkart, c. 1636 — tr. Catherine Winkworth, 1858}
{key: G}
{time: 4/4}
{tempo: 80}
{comment: Written during the Thirty Years' War, when Rinkart conducted 4,000 funerals in one year — including that of his wife. A hymn of thanksgiving in the face of devastation.}

{start_of_verse: 1}
[G]Now thank we [D]all our [G]God
[C]With heart and [G]hands and [D]voi[G]ces
[G]Who wondrous [D]things hath [G]done
[C]In whom His [G]world re[D]joi[G]ces
[D]Who, from our [G]mothers' [D]arms
[Em]Hath blessed us [Am]on our [D]way
[G]With countless [C]gifts of [G]love
[Am]And still is [D]ours to[G]day
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 2}
[G]O may this [D]bounteous [G]God
[C]Through all our [G]life be [D]near [G]us
[G]With ever [D]joyful [G]hearts
[C]And blessed [G]peace to [D]cheer [G]us
[D]And keep us [G]in His [D]grace
[Em]And guide us [Am]when per[D]plexed
[G]And free us [C]from all [G]ills
[Am]In this world [D]and the [G]next
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 3}
[G]All praise and [D]thanks to [G]God
[C]The Father, [G]now be [D]giv[G]en
[G]The Son, and [D]Him who [G]reigns
[C]With them in [G]highest [D]heav[G]en
[D]The one e[G]ternal [D]God
[Em]Whom earth and [Am]heav'n a[D]dore
[G]For thus it [C]was, is [G]now
[Am]And shall be [D]ever[G]more
{end_of_verse}
